README.md
     1вҶ’# python-dotenv
     3вҶ’[![Build Status][build_status_badge]][build_status_link]
     4вҶ’[![PyPI version][pypi_badge]][pypi_link]
     5вҶ’
     6вҶ’python-dotenv reads key-value pairs from a `.env` file and can set them as
     7вҶ’environment variables. It helps in the development of applications following the
     8вҶ’[12-factor](https://12factor.net/) principles.
     9вҶ’
    10вҶ’- [Getting Started](#getting-started)
    11вҶ’- [Other Use Cases](#other-use-cases)
    12вҶ’  - [Load configuration without altering the environment](#load-configuration-without-altering-the-environment)
    13вҶ’  - [Parse configuration as a stream](#parse-configuration-as-a-stream)
    14вҶ’  - [Load .env files in IPython](#load-env-files-in-ipython)
    15вҶ’- [Command-line Interface](#command-line-interface)
    16вҶ’- [File format](#file-format)
    17вҶ’  - [Multiline values](#multiline-values)
    18вҶ’  - [Variable expansion](#variable-expansion)
    19вҶ’- [Related Projects](#related-projects)
    20вҶ’- [Acknowledgements](#acknowledgements)
    21вҶ’
    22вҶ’## Getting Started
    24вҶ’```shell
    25вҶ’pip install python-dotenv
    26вҶ’```
    27вҶ’
    28вҶ’If your application takes its configuration from environment variables, like a
    29вҶ’12-factor application, launching it in development is not very practical because
    30вҶ’you have to set those environment variables yourself.
    31вҶ’
    32вҶ’To help you with that, you can add python-dotenv to your application to make it
    33вҶ’load the configuration from a `.env` file when it is present (e.g. in
    34вҶ’development) while remaining configurable via the environment:
    35вҶ’
    36вҶ’```python
    37вҶ’from dotenv import load_dotenv
    38вҶ’
    39вҶ’load_dotenv()  # reads variables from a .env file and sets them in os.environ
    40вҶ’
    41вҶ’# Code of your application, which uses environment variables (e.g. from `os.environ` or
    42вҶ’# `os.getenv`) as if they came from the actual environment.
    43вҶ’```
    44вҶ’
    45вҶ’By default, `load_dotenv()` will:
    46вҶ’
      вҶ’вҖҰ
    78вҶ’## Other Use Cases
    80вҶ’### Load configuration without altering the environment
    82вҶ’The function `dotenv_values` works more or less the same way as `load_dotenv`,
    83вҶ’except it doesn't touch the environment, it just returns a `dict` with the
    84вҶ’values parsed from the `.env` file.
    85вҶ’
    86вҶ’```python
      вҶ’вҖҰ
   105вҶ’### Parse configuration as a stream
   107вҶ’`load_dotenv` and `dotenv_values` accept [streams][python_streams] via their
   108вҶ’`stream` argument. It is thus possible to load the variables from sources other
   109вҶ’than the filesystem (e.g. the network).
   110вҶ’
   111вҶ’```python
      вҶ’вҖҰ
   120вҶ’### Load .env files in IPython
   122вҶ’You can use dotenv in IPython. By default, it will use `find_dotenv` to search for a
   123вҶ’`.env` file:
   124вҶ’
   125вҶ’```python
   126вҶ’%load_ext dotenv
      вҶ’вҖҰ
   141вҶ’### Disable load_dotenv
   143вҶ’Set `PYTHON_DOTENV_DISABLED=1` to disable `load_dotenv()` from loading .env
   144вҶ’files or streams. Useful when you can't modify third-party package calls or in
   145вҶ’production.
   146вҶ’
   147вҶ’## Command-line Interface
   149вҶ’A CLI interface `dotenv` is also included, which helps you manipulate the `.env`
   150вҶ’file without manually opening it.
   151вҶ’
   152вҶ’```shell
   153вҶ’$ pip install "python-dotenv[cli]"
   154вҶ’$ dotenv set USER foo
   155вҶ’$ dotenv set EMAIL foo@example.org
   156вҶ’$ dotenv list
   157вҶ’USER=foo
   158вҶ’EMAIL=foo@example.org
   159вҶ’$ dotenv list --format=json
   160вҶ’{
   161вҶ’  "USER": "foo",
   162вҶ’  "EMAIL": "foo@example.org"
   163вҶ’}
   164вҶ’$ dotenv run -- python foo.py
   165вҶ’```
   166вҶ’
   167вҶ’Run `dotenv --help` for more information about the options and subcommands.
   168вҶ’
   169вҶ’## File format
   171вҶ’The format is not formally specified and still improves over time. That being
   172вҶ’said, `.env` files should mostly look like Bash files. Reading from FIFOs (named
   173вҶ’pipes) on Unix systems is also supported.
   174вҶ’
   175вҶ’Keys can be unquoted or single-quoted. Values can be unquoted, single- or
   176вҶ’double-quoted. Spaces before and after keys, equal signs, and values are
   177вҶ’ignored. Values can be followed by a comment. Lines can start with the `export`
   178вҶ’directive, which does not affect their interpretation.
   179вҶ’
   180вҶ’Allowed escape sequences:
   181вҶ’
   182вҶ’- in single-quoted values: `\\`, `\'`
   183вҶ’- in double-quoted values: `\\`, `\'`, `\"`, `\a`, `\b`, `\f`, `\n`, `\r`, `\t`, `\v`
   184вҶ’
   185вҶ’### Multiline values
   187вҶ’It is possible for single- or double-quoted values to span multiple lines. The
   188вҶ’following examples are equivalent:
   189вҶ’
   190вҶ’```bash
   191вҶ’FOO="first line
      вҶ’вҖҰ
   199вҶ’### Variable without a value
   201вҶ’A variable can have no value:
   202вҶ’
   203вҶ’```bash
   204вҶ’FOO
   205вҶ’```
      вҶ’вҖҰ
   214вҶ’### Variable expansion
   216вҶ’python-dotenv can interpolate variables using POSIX variable expansion.
   217вҶ’
   218вҶ’With `load_dotenv(override=True)` or `dotenv_values()`, the value of a variable
   219вҶ’is the first of the values defined in the following list:
   220вҶ’
